WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:01:12.322 --> 00:01:13.532
[radar beeps]

3
00:01:24.751 --> 00:01:25.752
[typing]

4
00:01:36.388 --> 00:01:38.265
[aide 1] Sir. there's something
you need to see.

5
00:01:38.348 --> 00:01:40.184
[aide 2 speaks Russian]

6
00:01:40.267 --> 00:01:43.562
[aide 3] The asteroid must have
decayed from a near-Jovian Trojan orbit.

7
00:01:43.645 --> 00:01:45.856
which is why
we haven't been able to see it until now.

8
00:01:45.939 --> 00:01:48.442
Looks like it passed too close to Jupiter
on its last go-around

9
00:01:48.525 --> 00:01:51.236
and was redirected
into the inner solar system.

10
00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:54.990
[Margo] It appears to be coming in
on an elliptical Mars-crossing orbit.

11
00:01:55.073 --> 00:02:00.913
Looks like it's about 1.1 kilometers
in diameter. Not huge as these things go.

12
00:02:00.996 --> 00:02:03.665
And based on our orbital analysis
of its moon.

13
00:02:03.749 --> 00:02:06.793
the density of the asteroid is seven grams
per cubic centimeter.

14
00:02:06.877 --> 00:02:09.378
- Means it's full of metal. for sure.
- A special analysis tells us

15
00:02:09.463 --> 00:02:11.715
this asteroid
likely contains a colossal amount of...

16
00:02:11.798 --> 00:02:17.137
[in Russian] Iridium? Very rare on Earth.
And we already control most of it.

17
00:02:17.221 --> 00:02:18.889
Mmm. Not this much.

18
00:02:18.972 --> 00:02:25.062
A conservative guess is
70.000 metric tons.

19
00:02:25.145 --> 00:02:28.607
[in English] Our estimates indicate
there's more iridium in 2003LC

20
00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:30.943
than has been mined
in the entire history of Earth.

21
00:02:31.026 --> 00:02:34.196
Iridium is going for about 294 a gram.

22
00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:36.782
Based on current mass estimates.
that's worth upwards of...

23
00:02:36.865 --> 00:02:39.117
[Christine Francis]
...twenty trillion dollars and nicknamed

24
00:02:39.201 --> 00:02:40.744
the Goldilocks asteroid.

25
00:02:40.827 --> 00:02:44.831
If it is able to be harnessed
and its iridium mined in Mars orbit.

26
00:02:44.915 --> 00:02:49.586
economists predict it will lead to another
technological revolution here on Earth.

27
00:02:49.670 --> 00:02:52.047
[Chase] President Korzhenko
has expressed skepticism

28
00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:54.842
that the asteroid is in fact
made of iridium at all.

29
00:02:54.925 --> 00:02:58.554
insisting that the USSR
remains the only reliable supplier.

30
00:02:58.637 --> 00:02:59.638
[McGann] Let me remind you

31
00:02:59.721 --> 00:03:03.642
what happened after
NASA's last great discovery. Helium-3.

32
00:03:03.725 --> 00:03:07.020
Job cuts. protests. domestic terrorism.

33
00:03:07.104 --> 00:03:10.524
[news anchor] ...traveling through space
at tens of thousands of miles per hour.

34
00:03:10.607 --> 00:03:12.943
And the window to capture it
is closing quickly.

35
00:03:13.026 --> 00:03:15.153
In approximately six months.

36
00:03:15.237 --> 00:03:18.991
the asteroid's new trajectory will send it
out of reach for good.

37
00:04:42.533 --> 00:04:44.535
[crew chattering]

38
00:04:53.919 --> 00:04:55.712
[chattering continues]

39
00:05:52.811 --> 00:05:54.188
[Palmer] Commander Poole.

40
00:05:55.230 --> 00:05:56.315
Commander.

41
00:05:58.984 --> 00:06:00.068
[sighs]

42
00:06:00.777 --> 00:06:02.029
What time is it?

43
00:06:03.155 --> 00:06:05.199
It's nearly 1:00 a.m.. ma'am.

44
00:06:06.575 --> 00:06:08.785
But I thought it best to wake you.

45
00:06:10.204 --> 00:06:11.205
What's happened?

46
00:06:12.539 --> 00:06:14.124
Something incredible.

47
00:06:18.003 --> 00:06:21.340
[Gore. through speaker]
This asteroid. it's an amazing discovery.

48
00:06:21.423 --> 00:06:24.218
It is going to improve life on Earth
immeasurably.

49
00:06:24.885 --> 00:06:29.014
But if we fail to secure this valuable
resource for the American people.

50
00:06:29.681 --> 00:06:33.936
it'll not only be a black mark
on my administration. but on this country.

51
00:06:34.019 --> 00:06:36.563
I assure you. Mr. President.
we are doing everything we can

52
00:06:36.647 --> 00:06:38.273
to bring this one home for all of us.

53
00:06:38.357 --> 00:06:40.609
Good. I have faith in you. Eli.

54
00:06:40.692 --> 00:06:43.987
Especially with how you handled
the Zakharova situation this past spring.

55
00:06:44.655 --> 00:06:47.699
I'll let you and Ron hash out the details.
Keep me posted.

56
00:06:47.783 --> 00:06:48.909
[line clicks]

57
00:06:50.536 --> 00:06:51.537
Ron. I think you and I...

58
00:06:51.620 --> 00:06:54.122
So. how soon can we announce the plan
to harness the asteroid?

59
00:06:55.499 --> 00:06:58.001
- I'm sorry?
- I don't need to remind you that

60
00:06:58.085 --> 00:07:00.212
the president is headed
for a tough reelection battle.

61
00:07:00.295 --> 00:07:04.007
And the more the American people know
about what Goldilocks will do for them.

62
00:07:04.091 --> 00:07:05.551
the better his standing will get.

63
00:07:05.634 --> 00:07:08.804
Well. I hear you. Ron. I do.
But we have to be very delicate here.

64
00:07:09.388 --> 00:07:10.806
I'm already drowning in calls

65
00:07:10.889 --> 00:07:13.976
from the other M-7 nations
wanting a bigger piece of this pie.

66
00:07:14.059 --> 00:07:15.769
Not to mention.
the Soviets feel threatened

67
00:07:15.853 --> 00:07:18.522
because iridium happens to be
one of their biggest exports.

68
00:07:18.605 --> 00:07:20.274
We're on the same page here. Eli.

69
00:07:20.357 --> 00:07:22.651
The last thing we want to do is
antagonize our partners.

70
00:07:22.734 --> 00:07:26.989
Good. Because the only way we're gonna
get this thing is if we all work together.

71
00:07:27.072 --> 00:07:28.615
This can't be seen as just an American...

72
00:07:28.699 --> 00:07:31.577
You just focus on getting Mars
whatever it needs to get that asteroid.

73
00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:32.661
We'll handle the rest.

74
00:07:38.917 --> 00:07:41.879
[Danielle] Goldilocks is heading toward us
and hauling ass.

75
00:07:41.962 --> 00:07:46.925
So. we need to design and launch this
capture mission inside the next ten weeks.

76
00:07:47.009 --> 00:07:48.594
or else she gets away.

77
00:07:48.677 --> 00:07:50.929
That means pedal to the metal
for everybody.

78
00:07:51.013 --> 00:07:53.765
And all personal matters are gonna have
to take a back seat.

79
00:07:54.474 --> 00:07:58.353
Dimitri. how many more wranglers do you
think you'll need to corral this thing?

80
00:07:58.437 --> 00:08:02.858
Still waiting on protocols.
but at least ten more.

81
00:08:02.941 --> 00:08:07.571
Gonna have to ramp up microgravity
certification for many of my people.

82
00:08:07.654 --> 00:08:08.864
All right.

83
00:08:08.947 --> 00:08:11.867
If we're to have a hope in hell of
pulling this off. I strongly suggest that

84
00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:16.079
we curtail all but essential operations
and start stockpiling argon.

85
00:08:16.163 --> 00:08:18.874
Are you suggesting that
we slow down training operations?

86
00:08:18.957 --> 00:08:20.042
[Ed] Well. absolutely.

87
00:08:20.125 --> 00:08:23.003
Rushing around
with our hands flapping in the breeze.

88
00:08:23.086 --> 00:08:25.464
hoping we can wing it.
is not going to get this done.

89
00:08:25.547 --> 00:08:29.343
Well. rushing around with our hands
flapping wasn't what I was proposing. Ed.

90
00:08:29.426 --> 00:08:31.720
Well. it sure sounded like it to me.

91
00:08:42.397 --> 00:08:45.108
- Can I speak with you for a minute?
- Well. of course.

92
00:08:56.995 --> 00:08:58.872
Let's just get one thing straight.

93
00:08:58.956 --> 00:09:01.208
That attitude of yours.
it ain't gonna fly.

94
00:09:01.291 --> 00:09:04.336
What. I'm supposed to rubber-stamp
any harebrained idea of yours

95
00:09:04.419 --> 00:09:05.796
that washes over the transom?

96
00:09:05.879 --> 00:09:08.507
This is not about harebrained ideas. Ed.

97
00:09:08.590 --> 00:09:10.050
Ah. Then what is it about?

98
00:09:10.759 --> 00:09:11.760
[sighs]

99
00:09:13.011 --> 00:09:15.097
Let's just get this out in the open.
All right?

100
00:09:16.056 --> 00:09:18.934
Ever since I sent Svetlana Zakharova
back Earthside.

101
00:09:19.017 --> 00:09:20.602
you've been fighting me tooth and nail.

102
00:09:20.686 --> 00:09:22.688
I say "left." you say "right."

103
00:09:22.771 --> 00:09:27.067
It has slowed operations on Happy Valley
to a crawl these past few months.

104
00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:28.318
You're my XO.

105
00:09:28.986 --> 00:09:30.904
We have got to be on the same page.

106
00:09:30.988 --> 00:09:34.366
Sending her back was a bad call.

107
00:09:34.449 --> 00:09:35.617
[sighs]

108
00:09:35.701 --> 00:09:36.910
It hurt morale.

109
00:09:36.994 --> 00:09:39.204
It was my call to make.

110
00:09:40.205 --> 00:09:42.833
We don't have to see eye to eye on this
to get this thing done.

111
00:09:42.916 --> 00:09:45.419
But we need to get this thing done.

112
00:09:47.004 --> 00:09:52.301
This asteroid. Ed. it could
change everything for people back home.

113
00:09:52.384 --> 00:09:54.469
Isn't that why we're up here
in the first place?

114
00:09:56.138 --> 00:09:58.056
Look. I want to get this rock
as much as you do.

115
00:09:59.975 --> 00:10:00.976
Okay.

116
00:10:01.602 --> 00:10:04.938
Then let's cut the shit
and make this happen.

117
00:10:12.237 --> 00:10:16.366
- [laughs]
- [speaks indistinctly]

118
00:10:19.411 --> 00:10:20.704
I'll get this round.

119
00:10:23.790 --> 00:10:25.042
Four glasses. comrade.

120
00:10:26.084 --> 00:10:27.669
Uh. excuse me. Miles.

121
00:10:28.504 --> 00:10:30.839
Can I put in order
for these cotton shirts?

122
00:10:30.923 --> 00:10:33.133
Other fabric. it. uh. give me rash.

123
00:10:33.926 --> 00:10:35.969
- Sure thing.
- Grazie. comrade.

124
00:10:37.095 --> 00:10:38.096
Thank you.

125
00:10:40.849 --> 00:10:44.061
Next time he calls me comrade.
I'm going to punch him in the face.

126
00:10:44.144 --> 00:10:45.187
[chuckles]

127
00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:46.939
- Glass for you.
- Ooh.

128
00:10:47.022 --> 00:10:48.565
I don't like him.

129
00:10:49.358 --> 00:10:51.276
He's not good enough for Samantha.

130
00:10:53.529 --> 00:10:55.072
[chattering]

131
00:10:55.155 --> 00:10:57.991
[Ilya] Okay. Milosh.
What is next on the list?

132
00:10:58.075 --> 00:11:01.036
All right. all right.
Let's get back to it.

133
00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:06.667
Okay. so. today's haul. I got
another order from Staley for Odor-Eaters.

134
00:11:07.251 --> 00:11:09.503
He will not shut up about this.

135
00:11:09.586 --> 00:11:13.507
Oh. and. uh. Lee keeps asking me
about updates on his wife.

136
00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:15.551
We should let him know
where we stand on that.

137
00:11:15.634 --> 00:11:18.053
So. uh. where do we stand?

138
00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:20.764
Has your guy gotten the wife
out of North Korea?

139
00:11:21.431 --> 00:11:24.935
JAXA's next cargo launch to ISP is
in a couple of weeks.

140
00:11:25.018 --> 00:11:30.399
Unfortunately. we're not going to be able
to bring her up. after all.

141
00:11:32.734 --> 00:11:34.611
It's too risky. Milosh.

142
00:11:36.029 --> 00:11:38.198
Low profile. Remember?

143
00:11:38.282 --> 00:11:41.243
Okay. but you told him we were gonna
get it done. And I told him that too.

144
00:11:41.326 --> 00:11:45.122
- If he finds out that we were...
- Last thing we want is to anger him.

145
00:11:46.123 --> 00:11:48.876
Korean business has been very good to us.

146
00:11:48.959 --> 00:11:55.924
So. we must wait until right time
to say right thing.

147
00:11:56.008 --> 00:11:57.801
- Hmm?
- You mean lie to him?

148
00:11:58.385 --> 00:12:01.138
You worry too much. Milosh. [chuckles]

149
00:12:01.805 --> 00:12:05.434
Remember. Ilya knows best. Eh?

150
00:12:07.019 --> 00:12:09.354
The capture mission's
just the tip of the spear.

151
00:12:09.438 --> 00:12:12.232
They're gonna need us to make
hundreds of thousands of liters of fuel.

152
00:12:12.316 --> 00:12:13.317
replacement parts...

153
00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:15.235
We'll be mining that thing for decades.

154
00:12:15.319 --> 00:12:17.446
They're gonna have to build
Happy Valley out big time.

155
00:12:17.529 --> 00:12:18.530
Thousands more workers.

156
00:12:18.614 --> 00:12:22.326
Right. it's like. uh. gold rush. No?
Bonuses. overtime. hazard pay...

157
00:12:22.409 --> 00:12:24.912
Well. I heard that we're gonna be working
round the clock.

158
00:12:26.079 --> 00:12:28.999
Double shifts. Six. seven days.

159
00:12:29.082 --> 00:12:30.876
And I mean. they're asking us to do this

160
00:12:30.959 --> 00:12:33.086
in half of the time
of what we should have.

161
00:12:34.129 --> 00:12:36.173
Samantha's right. We must be careful.

162
00:12:36.673 --> 00:12:38.592
But it is also an amazing opportunity. no?

163
00:12:38.675 --> 00:12:41.386
Perhaps you will be assigned
to the Ranger crew again.

164
00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.388
Glass half full. That is how you say it?

165
00:12:43.472 --> 00:12:45.224
[laughs] Something like that.

166
00:12:46.934 --> 00:12:48.018
To Goldilocks.

167
00:12:49.061 --> 00:12:51.813
[reporter] Eighty-four percent of voters
who own cell phones

168
00:12:51.897 --> 00:12:57.819
say they support a proposed state ban on
the use of handheld phones while driving.

169
00:12:58.779 --> 00:13:01.281
Alex. we're leaving for school
in five minutes.

170
00:13:01.365 --> 00:13:02.658
[Alex] Okay.

171
00:13:02.741 --> 00:13:05.244
Peanut butter jelly not proper lunch.

172
00:13:05.827 --> 00:13:07.746
Well. Alex loves it. so...

173
00:13:07.829 --> 00:13:11.625
...central to the initial race to Mars.
is finally going himself.

174
00:13:12.209 --> 00:13:13.877
Dev Ayesa has announced

175
00:13:13.961 --> 00:13:18.340
he is finally making the journey
to the red planet later this month.

176
00:13:18.423 --> 00:13:20.259
Ayesa talked with reporters today...

177
00:13:20.342 --> 00:13:22.803
- Shit.
- ...outside his Helios offices.

178
00:13:23.428 --> 00:13:26.306
[Dev] I simply felt that as CEO of Helios.

179
00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:28.892
with everything unfolding
on Mars as it has.

180
00:13:28.976 --> 00:13:31.103
that I should take a more hands-on role
up there.

181
00:13:41.071 --> 00:13:44.074
- What's going on?
- Guess you haven't heard the news?

182
00:13:46.493 --> 00:13:51.874
That might be something you wanna tell us
before announcing it to the whole world.

183
00:13:52.791 --> 00:13:54.293
It was a spontaneous decision.

184
00:13:54.376 --> 00:13:56.587
You going to Mars was
a spontaneous decision?

185
00:13:57.296 --> 00:13:59.214
- Yes.
- [Aleida] Dev. I know out there you can do

186
00:13:59.298 --> 00:14:01.425
whatever you want and
people kiss your ass regardless.

187
00:14:01.508 --> 00:14:04.678
But in here. in these offices.
we're actually trying to get shit done.

188
00:14:04.761 --> 00:14:06.930
- and you throwing this kind of curveball...
- I know.

189
00:14:07.014 --> 00:14:10.350
And you and your team have been killing it
developing the asteroid capture plan.

190
00:14:10.434 --> 00:14:12.311
but the real action is up there.

191
00:14:12.394 --> 00:14:15.731
And as leader of this company.
I got to go where I'm needed most.

192
00:14:15.814 --> 00:14:17.316
So. if you're up there.

193
00:14:17.399 --> 00:14:20.485
who's going to handle
all the M-7 negotiations for Goldilocks?

194
00:14:21.778 --> 00:14:23.989
No way. I'm an engineer. I'm not...

195
00:14:24.072 --> 00:14:27.117
Aleida. don't worry. You'll be great.

196
00:14:27.618 --> 00:14:29.286
Now. Kelly.
we need to talk about robotics.

197
00:14:29.369 --> 00:14:32.789
So. I guess the astrobiology program just
gets shunted aside.

198
00:14:33.290 --> 00:14:35.209
- Back burner yet again. right?
- On the contrary.

199
00:14:35.292 --> 00:14:36.376
I'm escalating the timeline.

200
00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:39.046
I want your team's personnel
and equipment with me when I go.

201
00:14:39.129 --> 00:14:43.509
Okay. The seekers can be ready.
but I doubt my expedition team will be.

202
00:14:43.592 --> 00:14:46.011
I was counting on another six weeks
to bring them up to speed.

203
00:14:46.094 --> 00:14:47.387
I have a fix for that.

204
00:14:48.430 --> 00:14:49.765
You come with us.

205
00:14:51.225 --> 00:14:52.267
What?

206
00:14:52.351 --> 00:14:54.061
[Dev] You train your team en route.

207
00:14:54.144 --> 00:14:57.272
By the time we arrive. they'll be ready
to hit the ground running.

208
00:14:57.356 --> 00:14:59.441
[scoffs] Dev. I-I hear what you're saying.

209
00:14:59.525 --> 00:15:02.319
but I can't just drop everything
and go to Mars with you.

210
00:15:02.402 --> 00:15:03.403
Why not?

211
00:15:03.987 --> 00:15:05.197
I have a son.

212
00:15:05.739 --> 00:15:08.784
I-I'd have to leave him behind for what.
six months. a year. Maybe longer.

213
00:15:08.867 --> 00:15:11.787
You have spent 15 years
on the search for life.

214
00:15:12.621 --> 00:15:15.832
It would be a shame to drop the ball
when you're this close to the finish line.

215
00:15:19.002 --> 00:15:20.087
But it's up to you.

216
00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:25.717
Meanwhile. I got a few loose ends that
I need to tie up before I go.

217
00:15:25.801 --> 00:15:28.011
so I will be out of pocket
for a couple of days.

218
00:15:28.095 --> 00:15:31.765
A couple of days? But we're right in
the middle of revamping capture protocols.

219
00:15:38.772 --> 00:15:40.691
[Danielle. through radio]
Ranger. Happy Valley.

220
00:15:40.774 --> 00:15:44.611
Ed. I see that you made some changes
to the Ranger-2 crew list.

221
00:15:44.695 --> 00:15:46.446
You know that needs to be run by me first.

222
00:15:46.530 --> 00:15:47.948
- [line clicks]
- Come on. Danielle.

223
00:15:48.031 --> 00:15:52.119
You know as well as I do that the mission
commander customarily picks his own crew.

224
00:15:52.202 --> 00:15:54.329
This isn't NASA in the '70s. Ed.

225
00:15:54.413 --> 00:15:57.875
Ultimately. I'm responsible
for getting Goldilocks into Mars orbit.

226
00:15:57.958 --> 00:16:01.461
Affirmative. Now. what's the problem?

227
00:16:01.545 --> 00:16:03.630
Disregard of protocol. for one.

228
00:16:03.714 --> 00:16:07.009
This should have been run past me
before being distributed. but let's just...

229
00:16:07.092 --> 00:16:09.136
Let's put that to the side. all right.

230
00:16:09.219 --> 00:16:13.182
This crew list. it's cherry-picked
based off of what metrics?

231
00:16:13.265 --> 00:16:15.642
Well. after
the commissioner's blame-game report

232
00:16:15.726 --> 00:16:18.020
about the Kronos clusterfuck came out.

233
00:16:18.103 --> 00:16:20.689
I thought it would be good
to shake things up here and there.

234
00:16:20.772 --> 00:16:26.111
So. some crew members were replaced
and others were deemed mission essential.

235
00:16:26.195 --> 00:16:28.655
- Like you as commander?
- Yeah.

236
00:16:28.739 --> 00:16:33.911
Experienced commander. Battle-tested.
It sounded like a goddamn winner to me.

237
00:16:33.994 --> 00:16:38.415
But hell. if you wanna micromanage me like
this. we can start all over. No problem.

238
00:16:39.625 --> 00:16:41.877
Negative. XO. Negative.

239
00:16:42.377 --> 00:16:43.545
Your crew stands.

240
00:16:44.171 --> 00:16:48.258
Just give me more of a heads-up next time.
Happy Valley out.

241
00:16:48.342 --> 00:16:49.343
[line clicks]

242
00:16:50.052 --> 00:16:51.261
[Ed] Goddamn it.

243
00:16:52.054 --> 00:16:55.057
Switching back to manual
for attitude control checkout.

244
00:16:55.140 --> 00:16:57.559
[crew member 1] Copy that.
We're go for RCS manual test.

245
00:16:58.185 --> 00:16:59.269
[Ed grunts]

246
00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:01.313
Uh. hold on that test for a minute.

247
00:17:02.564 --> 00:17:03.607
Standing by. Ranger.

248
00:17:06.276 --> 00:17:07.653
You okay. sir?

249
00:17:07.736 --> 00:17:08.737
Yeah. I'm fine.

250
00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:11.531
Don't forget
to cross-check the reactor temps

251
00:17:11.615 --> 00:17:13.742
before we disembark for Phoenix.
all right?

252
00:17:15.035 --> 00:17:16.036
Aye. aye.

253
00:17:22.166 --> 00:17:26.213
You gotta go. You can't give this
opportunity up because you have a kid.

254
00:17:26.713 --> 00:17:30.634
- You think guys ever have to do that?
- Course not. but Alex is different.

255
00:17:30.717 --> 00:17:31.760
You know that.

256
00:17:31.844 --> 00:17:33.679
With his health issues and...

257
00:17:34.471 --> 00:17:37.182
- He just needs me here.
- He has his grandma.

258
00:17:37.266 --> 00:17:39.309
[scoffs] Yeah.
and she'd probably love it if I left.

259
00:17:39.393 --> 00:17:41.854
so she can take him back to Russia
the first chance she gets.

260
00:17:44.565 --> 00:17:49.570
I just couldn't live with myself if he
felt like I was abandoning him. you know.

261
00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:51.071
Hey.

262
00:17:51.989 --> 00:17:53.782
Kids are more resilient than you know.

263
00:17:54.950 --> 00:17:56.952
I just don't want him to end up hating me.

264
00:17:57.035 --> 00:17:59.288
Oh. he's going to hate you no matter what.
Believe me.

265
00:17:59.371 --> 00:18:01.373
Is that supposed to make me feel better?

266
00:18:01.456 --> 00:18:02.791
It's just what happens.

267
00:18:02.875 --> 00:18:05.586
You give them life.
you give them everything from yourself.

268
00:18:05.669 --> 00:18:07.504
and then they end up looking at you

269
00:18:07.588 --> 00:18:09.715
like you're the most vile human that
ever lived.

270
00:18:10.799 --> 00:18:13.385
I'm sorry. I'm... I'm sure that isn't easy.

271
00:18:14.052 --> 00:18:15.804
What goes around comes around.

272
00:18:17.055 --> 00:18:19.099
I really put my poor dad
through the wringer.

273
00:18:20.517 --> 00:18:22.519
Well. I'm sure
he'd be very proud of you now.

274
00:18:23.770 --> 00:18:25.939
Aleida Rosales. power broker.

275
00:18:26.023 --> 00:18:29.651
God. Oh. God. no.
It's gonna be a disaster. Just you watch.

276
00:18:30.736 --> 00:18:33.488
I don't know. I think you have it in you.

277
00:18:33.572 --> 00:18:37.868
Come on. Can you imagine me
sitting across from all those M-7 reps?

278
00:18:37.951 --> 00:18:39.953
Yes. I can.

279
00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:44.249
Look. I remember my mom
when she first bought this place.

280
00:18:44.333 --> 00:18:47.085
Okay. she'd never run a business
before in her life.

281
00:18:47.669 --> 00:18:49.546
I asked her if she was nervous. She said.

282
00:18:50.839 --> 00:18:53.717
"There are always a million reasons
not to do something.

283
00:18:54.843 --> 00:18:56.803
You have to find the reason to do it."

284
00:19:06.271 --> 00:19:09.316
[Gore] The American
Space Program is central to that.

285
00:19:09.399 --> 00:19:11.902
And during my time as your president.

286
00:19:11.985 --> 00:19:18.617
I took the initiative in discovering
this incredibly valuable asteroid. 2003LC.

287
00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:23.080
A discovery that will change our country
and our world for the better.

288
00:19:23.163 --> 00:19:26.667
President Gore today appeared
to take personal responsibility

289
00:19:26.750 --> 00:19:29.795
for the discovery of asteroid 2003LC.

290
00:19:29.878 --> 00:19:32.381
The Kremlin has denounced Gore's
claim of personal responsibility

291
00:19:32.464 --> 00:19:34.675
for the asteroid discovery as an
outrageous attempt

292
00:19:34.758 --> 00:19:36.593
to take credit for a Soviet achievement.

293
00:19:36.677 --> 00:19:39.304
But here now.
other achievements claimed by Al Gore.

294
00:19:39.388 --> 00:19:42.975
Number ten. was first human being
to grow an opposable thumb.

295
00:19:43.058 --> 00:19:44.059
[audience laughs]

296
00:19:44.142 --> 00:19:47.688
Number nine. while riding bicycle one day.
accidentally invented the orgasm.

297
00:19:47.771 --> 00:19:50.816
It looks like
the president has stepped in it again.

298
00:19:50.899 --> 00:19:53.986
Next he'll want to name the asteroid
"Tipper."

299
00:19:54.695 --> 00:19:58.156
My advice. Al.
leave the discoveries to the scientists

300
00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:01.994
and stick to doing what you do best.
ruining our economy.

301
00:20:02.661 --> 00:20:07.833
What the hell is he doing?
This is a dance. Ron. A delicate dance.

302
00:20:07.916 --> 00:20:10.043
I don't control what the president says.
You know that.

303
00:20:10.127 --> 00:20:12.087
Don't give me that shit.
It was a prepared speech.

304
00:20:12.171 --> 00:20:14.423
He was reading off a fucking teleprompter.

305
00:20:14.506 --> 00:20:15.883
He likes to improvise sometimes.

306
00:20:16.466 --> 00:20:19.011
This is going to destroy
all of the goodwill

307
00:20:19.094 --> 00:20:20.888
that we have built up with the Russians.

308
00:20:20.971 --> 00:20:24.057
And do you have any idea
of what the other M-7 nations are gonna...

309
00:20:24.141 --> 00:20:27.436
Yeah. and none of it matters
if we lose to Bragg in '04.

310
00:20:27.519 --> 00:20:29.980
- Oh. so that's what this is all about?
- Of course it is.

311
00:20:30.063 --> 00:20:33.275
You and I both know that Bragg would be
a fucking nightmare for NASA.

312
00:20:33.358 --> 00:20:36.361
Not to mention the country.
So. let's get off our soapbox.

313
00:20:41.825 --> 00:20:42.826
Fuck.

314
00:20:47.039 --> 00:20:48.916
Oh. shit.

315
00:20:50.584 --> 00:20:54.213
I don't see how Ranger is gonna
despin something as big as Goldilocks.

316
00:20:54.296 --> 00:20:56.256
The ion engines just don't generate
enough thrust.

317
00:20:56.340 --> 00:20:57.341
I hear ya.

318
00:20:58.050 --> 00:20:59.051
I hear ya.

319
00:20:59.635 --> 00:21:03.305
All right. people. Let's keep thinking
on this. In the meantime.

320
00:21:03.388 --> 00:21:06.975
I wanna see some hard data from
those 3-D torque simulations by tomorrow.

321
00:21:07.518 --> 00:21:08.977
- Thanks. guys.
- All right. Thank you.

322
00:21:18.028 --> 00:21:19.071
[Palmer sighs]

323
00:21:24.952 --> 00:21:26.537
- Palmer.
- Yes. ma'am.

324
00:21:27.037 --> 00:21:30.249
You gonna lurk round my door all day long.
or you gonna tell me what's on your mind?

325
00:21:31.166 --> 00:21:32.167
[sighs]

326
00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:35.003
- Uh. Do you mind if I...
- Go ahead.

327
00:21:39.132 --> 00:21:40.133
Take a seat.

328
00:21:46.348 --> 00:21:48.433
- [Palmer clears throat]
- What's on your mind?

329
00:21:50.102 --> 00:21:51.270
Well. I. um...

330
00:21:52.145 --> 00:21:54.690
First off. I-I-I just wanna say that. uh.

331
00:21:55.732 --> 00:21:56.817
Admiral Baldwin.

332
00:21:58.443 --> 00:22:00.779
he's basically a hero to me.

333
00:22:02.406 --> 00:22:05.617
I was seven when the Russkies beat us
to the Moon.

334
00:22:06.410 --> 00:22:10.247
and my dad and I. we saw
all those congressional hearings.

335
00:22:11.164 --> 00:22:14.751
When Admiral Baldwin took the blame
for losing the Moon.

336
00:22:16.545 --> 00:22:18.005
he was talking about honor.

337
00:22:19.798 --> 00:22:26.096
He was talking about taking responsibility
even when it's difficult.

338
00:22:29.016 --> 00:22:30.142
[sighs]

339
00:22:31.602 --> 00:22:35.397
When we were out on Ranger.
I. um... I saw something.

340
00:22:36.273 --> 00:22:38.775
And God's honest truth.
I-I-I wish I hadn't.

341
00:22:40.569 --> 00:22:41.653
But I did.

342
00:22:42.654 --> 00:22:46.450
And now I feel compelled to report it.

343
00:22:47.534 --> 00:22:48.535
Okay.

344
00:22:51.413 --> 00:22:56.877
Admiral Baldwin has a tremor
or something with his right hand.

345
00:22:58.962 --> 00:23:00.797
And I could tell he was trying to hide it.

346
00:23:02.341 --> 00:23:05.010
He had to halt a training exercise
because of it.

347
00:23:09.097 --> 00:23:11.808
Are you saying that
Ed is hiding a medical condition?

348
00:23:12.518 --> 00:23:14.978
That is what I suspect. Commander. Yes.

349
00:23:18.232 --> 00:23:20.776
That is a very serious accusation.

350
00:23:22.069 --> 00:23:23.111
I know it is.

351
00:23:24.696 --> 00:23:26.823
But I also know what I saw.

352
00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:29.701
I just thought you should know too.

353
00:23:31.370 --> 00:23:32.371
[sighs]

354
00:23:32.955 --> 00:23:34.623
All right. That'll be all.

355
00:23:34.706 --> 00:23:35.916
Yeah. [clears throat]

356
00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:39.002
[Palmer sighs]

357
00:23:44.591 --> 00:23:45.592
[sighs]

358
00:24:19.418 --> 00:24:21.128
- [device beeps]
- [door lock clicks]

359
00:24:50.073 --> 00:24:51.950
[Danielle] Now. make sure to ration this.

360
00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:55.621
It's gotta last you another four weeks.

361
00:25:00.667 --> 00:25:01.752
Danielle?

362
00:25:16.433 --> 00:25:17.935
Can I please come back?

363
00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:20.604
Please.

364
00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:23.815
I'll stay in my rack. I'll-I'll...

365
00:25:23.899 --> 00:25:25.025
I'm sorry.

366
00:25:26.443 --> 00:25:27.611
I know it's hard.

367
00:25:28.904 --> 00:25:30.405
but this is how it's gotta be.

368
00:25:31.657 --> 00:25:32.950
You know that.

369
00:25:40.082 --> 00:25:41.124
[Danielle sighs]

370
00:26:03.814 --> 00:26:05.566
Help. Captain. They're shooting us.

371
00:26:05.649 --> 00:26:07.651
[imitating gunfire]

372
00:26:08.151 --> 00:26:09.903
Abandon ship. We're going down.

373
00:26:10.445 --> 00:26:11.947
[imitates ship crashing]

374
00:26:13.115 --> 00:26:15.576
Help! I'm on fire. [shouts]

375
00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:18.412
Hey. baby.

376
00:26:18.912 --> 00:26:20.831
Hi. Mommy. Do you wanna play with me?

377
00:26:20.914 --> 00:26:22.499
Sure. bud. In a little bit.

378
00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.294
I wanna talk to you about something first.

379
00:26:27.254 --> 00:26:29.506
You know how I'm going
to send my robots to Mars

380
00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:31.258
to look for
those little microbes up there?

381
00:26:31.341 --> 00:26:33.385
- In the lava tubes.
- That's right.

382
00:26:33.468 --> 00:26:38.640
Anyway. it... it looks like
I might need to go with them.

383
00:26:38.724 --> 00:26:40.058
To Mars?

384
00:26:40.934 --> 00:26:43.437
But while I'm gone.
you'll stay here with grandma.

385
00:26:46.273 --> 00:26:47.524
Why can't I come?

386
00:26:49.943 --> 00:26:52.988
Well. for one. you're still in school.

387
00:26:53.739 --> 00:26:55.699
and space travel isn't
really for kids yet.

388
00:26:55.782 --> 00:26:58.869
But Zack's mom and dad took him
to this hotel place on the Moon

389
00:26:58.952 --> 00:27:00.204
when we were in second grade.

390
00:27:00.287 --> 00:27:03.290
Well. yes. But it only takes a day
to get to the Moon.

391
00:27:03.832 --> 00:27:06.168
and it takes much longer to get to Mars.

392
00:27:08.420 --> 00:27:09.922
How long will you be gone?

393
00:27:12.758 --> 00:27:13.800
About a year.

394
00:27:15.010 --> 00:27:17.221
I know it seems like a long time

395
00:27:18.347 --> 00:27:20.224
but it'll go by so quickly.

396
00:27:21.141 --> 00:27:22.142
You'll see.

397
00:27:22.226 --> 00:27:26.355
What if you decide to stay forever
like Poppy did?

398
00:27:26.438 --> 00:27:30.275
Aw. bud. I know this is hard
but I've been on work trips before.

399
00:27:30.359 --> 00:27:32.444
This one will just be a bit longer. okay?

400
00:27:34.947 --> 00:27:36.323
Alex. come back. I...

401
00:27:40.619 --> 00:27:41.828
Alex.

402
00:27:43.497 --> 00:27:46.041
[shushes] It's okay. It's okay.

403
00:27:46.667 --> 00:27:48.043
[shushes]

404
00:27:48.919 --> 00:27:50.212
[Alex sniffling]

405
00:27:50.796 --> 00:27:52.589
[in Russian]
It will all be okay. little one.

406
00:27:54.716 --> 00:27:56.426
It will all be okay.

407
00:27:57.803 --> 00:27:58.846
[shushes]

408
00:28:10.858 --> 00:28:13.485
[in English] Hey. Aleida. right? Aleida?

409
00:28:13.569 --> 00:28:14.695
So nice to meet you.

410
00:28:14.778 --> 00:28:17.030
I'm Brandt. Government relations.

411
00:28:17.114 --> 00:28:19.491
And obviously. we're going to be
working pretty close together

412
00:28:19.575 --> 00:28:21.118
with everything that's been decided.

413
00:28:21.201 --> 00:28:24.496
So. we really need to finalize
which senators we're approaching

414
00:28:24.580 --> 00:28:28.625
to support our position with the M-7.
Have you looked at the dossiers?

415
00:28:30.002 --> 00:28:32.212
Yeah. Yes. I have.

416
00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:37.509
Uh. still doing a bit more. you know. um...

417
00:28:38.719 --> 00:28:39.928
Mulling it over.

418
00:28:40.429 --> 00:28:43.348
Ins and outs.

419
00:28:43.432 --> 00:28:46.685
- You haven't looked at it yet.
- Have you talked to Dev at all about this?

420
00:28:46.768 --> 00:28:49.396
I feel like he might have an opinion.

421
00:28:49.479 --> 00:28:53.483
Mm-hmm. He. uh. told us
we should just come to you.

422
00:28:53.567 --> 00:28:56.570
So. uh. just take a look
at those dossiers. okay?

423
00:28:57.321 --> 00:28:58.906
[footsteps departing]

424
00:29:04.536 --> 00:29:09.917
And. uh. this is the entryway
and this is the living room.

425
00:29:10.584 --> 00:29:13.420
You know. it's not the biggest
but it's got a fireplace.

426
00:29:13.504 --> 00:29:19.301
And there is the kitchen
with this little. uh. eat-in nook there.

427
00:29:20.302 --> 00:29:21.970
[sighs] It's gonna be really nice

428
00:29:22.054 --> 00:29:24.765
cooking the girls' breakfast
in the morning before school.

429
00:29:24.848 --> 00:29:26.975
[kids squealing. laughing]

430
00:29:27.059 --> 00:29:29.353
- [Sarah] I'm gonna get you!
- [Mandy laughs]

431
00:29:29.436 --> 00:29:32.439
[Mandy]
Oh. and wait for the best part. [laughs]

432
00:29:33.607 --> 00:29:35.442
This is Sarah's room.

433
00:29:35.526 --> 00:29:38.779
- and over there. that's Lily's room.
- [Lily] And this is my room!

434
00:29:38.862 --> 00:29:40.531
- [Mandy chuckles]
- [Lily] No!

435
00:29:41.698 --> 00:29:44.159
And. um. over there is our room.

436
00:29:44.660 --> 00:29:47.246
I mean. um. my room.

437
00:29:47.329 --> 00:29:51.708
Uh. but you know.
when you get back we'll talk. [chuckles]

438
00:29:51.792 --> 00:29:54.378
Uh. anyway. [chuckles]

439
00:29:55.128 --> 00:29:57.714
We're just so excited. Miles.

440
00:29:57.798 --> 00:29:59.883
I... I can't believe that

441
00:30:00.801 --> 00:30:04.972
we can finally
buy our own house thanks to you.

442
00:30:05.764 --> 00:30:09.893
Honestly. I... I never thought that
we'd be able to do that.

443
00:30:12.896 --> 00:30:14.898
[chuckles]

444
00:30:14.982 --> 00:30:17.401
Okay. Gotta go. Bye.

445
00:30:17.484 --> 00:30:18.485
[line clicks]

446
00:30:28.495 --> 00:30:29.496
[Sam sighs]

447
00:30:33.250 --> 00:30:34.251
[Miles] You okay?

448
00:30:35.377 --> 00:30:38.130
Yeah. They. uh... They posted
the assignments for Goldilocks.

449
00:30:39.631 --> 00:30:41.550
Ah. shit.
You didn't get on the Ranger. huh?

450
00:30:42.342 --> 00:30:43.802
Bastards. why don't they realize...

451
00:30:43.886 --> 00:30:46.722
No. no. I... I did. I. um... [sighs]

452
00:30:46.805 --> 00:30:50.309
I... I got on. I am... [chuckles]

453
00:30:50.934 --> 00:30:52.102
I'm on the crew.

454
00:30:52.186 --> 00:30:55.272
Well. shit. That's great. isn't it?
I mean. that's what you wanted.

455
00:30:55.355 --> 00:30:56.565
Yeah. I know. [chuckles]

456
00:30:57.941 --> 00:31:00.903
I know. I've been banging my head
against the wall these past few months.

457
00:31:00.986 --> 00:31:03.197
trying to get back out there. and now I...

458
00:31:05.532 --> 00:31:07.159
[chuckles]

459
00:31:07.242 --> 00:31:10.162
Miles. you should've fucking seen us
out there.

460
00:31:10.245 --> 00:31:14.833
We... All running up to that board.
looking for our names. you know.

461
00:31:14.917 --> 00:31:19.463
Praying we got a slot. Thinking that
we won the... the fucking lottery.

462
00:31:20.464 --> 00:31:23.634
When... When the truth is we are
powerless up here. Miles.

463
00:31:24.468 --> 00:31:26.178
That's what I keep telling you.

464
00:31:26.261 --> 00:31:28.180
Come in with me
on this red obsidian thing.

465
00:31:28.263 --> 00:31:29.306
It's not too late.

466
00:31:29.389 --> 00:31:31.183
People back home are paying anything

467
00:31:31.266 --> 00:31:34.102
to get a piece of Mars. That way
you're not putting your life on the line

468
00:31:34.186 --> 00:31:36.271
for people
who don't give a shit about you.

469
00:31:38.357 --> 00:31:40.901
No. I don't know.
I don't think I'm there yet.

470
00:31:40.984 --> 00:31:44.988
I've been wanting this my whole life.
you know? I can't just walk away from it.

471
00:31:47.783 --> 00:31:48.825
Yeah. I get it.

472
00:33:07.362 --> 00:33:08.906
[people chattering]

473
00:33:16.038 --> 00:33:18.248
- [Dev] Looking for Malaika.
- She's right over there.

474
00:33:18.332 --> 00:33:19.333
Thank you.

475
00:33:24.213 --> 00:33:26.340
William. move the left side up.

476
00:33:26.423 --> 00:33:28.217
It needs to be straight.

477
00:33:29.843 --> 00:33:30.844
Higher.

478
00:33:35.682 --> 00:33:36.975
Well.

479
00:33:37.601 --> 00:33:40.604
My goodness. What a nice surprise.

480
00:33:47.110 --> 00:33:48.111
Come.

481
00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:53.075
God be praised.

482
00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:56.453
Let me look at you.

483
00:34:07.422 --> 00:34:08.715
Are you hungry?

484
00:34:09.675 --> 00:34:10.926
No. I already ate.

485
00:34:12.261 --> 00:34:13.804
I came to say goodbye.

486
00:34:14.638 --> 00:34:15.681
Goodbye?

487
00:34:16.806 --> 00:34:17.975
I'm going to Mars.

488
00:34:21.562 --> 00:34:23.480
We're doing something important up there.

489
00:34:24.982 --> 00:34:27.568
We're building a new world
and it's a better world than this one.

490
00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:30.027
You know
you could try to change things here.

491
00:34:30.612 --> 00:34:32.697
You could make such a difference. Dev.

492
00:34:32.781 --> 00:34:34.616
When you come back. there is a community...

493
00:34:34.699 --> 00:34:36.076
I'm not coming back.

494
00:34:36.659 --> 00:34:37.661
What do you mean?

495
00:34:38.579 --> 00:34:39.830
I'm staying up there.

496
00:34:42.081 --> 00:34:44.543
You're still chasing your father's dream.
aren't you?

497
00:34:45.043 --> 00:34:46.587
I'm not doing this for him.

498
00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:52.509
That's what you tell yourself. But these
dreams of space destroyed your father.

499
00:34:52.592 --> 00:34:54.636
Space did not destroy him.

500
00:34:56.179 --> 00:34:57.097
You did.

501
00:34:59.725 --> 00:35:03.061
Everything that he did.
he did for his family.

502
00:35:03.729 --> 00:35:05.189
For our future.

503
00:35:06.356 --> 00:35:09.985
He never recovered after you left us.

504
00:35:10.068 --> 00:35:12.529
I never left you. my son. You know this.

505
00:35:12.613 --> 00:35:14.656
I was there. Don't you remember?

506
00:35:14.740 --> 00:35:17.910
Oh. yes. I remember how I begged you
to come with me.

507
00:35:17.993 --> 00:35:21.914
And you wanted me to leave him
with no one at all? I could never do that.

508
00:35:21.997 --> 00:35:26.168
The truth is. he had already infected you
with his disease of ambition.

509
00:35:26.251 --> 00:35:28.545
Okay. God forbid
anybody have any ambition.

510
00:35:32.299 --> 00:35:36.178
Let's just agree that you and I will never
see eye to eye and part as friends.

511
00:35:36.261 --> 00:35:39.348
You're not my friend. You're my son.

512
00:35:40.516 --> 00:35:44.436
Stay here with me. With your people.
Don't turn your back on them.

513
00:35:44.937 --> 00:35:49.650
You can do so much good
for the young ones. They look up to you.

514
00:35:51.777 --> 00:35:53.487
Harambee. right?

515
00:35:53.570 --> 00:35:56.865
Everybody joining hands. working together
for the good of the whole. You know.

516
00:35:57.574 --> 00:35:59.076
of all the lies that you told me.

517
00:36:00.244 --> 00:36:01.828
that one was the cruelest one.

518
00:36:04.998 --> 00:36:08.168
But it's okay
because I see how people are now.

519
00:36:12.172 --> 00:36:14.758
If you need anything.

520
00:36:14.842 --> 00:36:15.968
just call this number.

521
00:36:21.807 --> 00:36:23.600
I don't want your money.

522
00:36:24.560 --> 00:36:26.270
I never wanted it.

523
00:36:27.187 --> 00:36:29.231
I just want my son.

524
00:36:35.070 --> 00:36:36.071
Goodbye. Mother.

525
00:36:49.793 --> 00:36:52.880
I understand how you feel and I apologize.

526
00:36:52.963 --> 00:36:55.674
[chuckles] The president just got
a little carried away. that's all.

527
00:36:55.757 --> 00:36:59.344
He made a grave insult
to the honor of the Soviet Union.

528
00:36:59.428 --> 00:37:01.597
I will issue a statement to clarify

529
00:37:01.680 --> 00:37:04.558
the Soviet Union's crucial role
in the discovery.

530
00:37:04.641 --> 00:37:07.019
You must understand. Administrator Hobson.

531
00:37:07.603 --> 00:37:11.398
President Korzhenko also faces
enormous political pressure.

532
00:37:12.441 --> 00:37:17.029
Members of the politburo are urging him
to go after the asteroid ourselves.

533
00:37:17.112 --> 00:37:20.908
Irina. you know as well as I do that
neither one of us have the capability

534
00:37:20.991 --> 00:37:22.784
to grab this rock on our own.

535
00:37:22.868 --> 00:37:25.996
Are we really going
to let an amazing opportunity like this

536
00:37:26.079 --> 00:37:29.082
slip through our fingers
'cause of one little screwup?

537
00:37:29.166 --> 00:37:34.880
I think the best course.
in the light of your president's behavior.

538
00:37:34.963 --> 00:37:36.590
is to negotiate a new agreement

539
00:37:36.673 --> 00:37:37.883
- that specifies...
- [scoffs]

540
00:37:37.966 --> 00:37:39.676
...how we will divide up the asteroid.

541
00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:43.138
What is the point of previous agreements
if we keep tearing them up?

542
00:37:43.222 --> 00:37:48.936
It would mollify the hard-liners in our
politburo. as well as Dev Ayesa at Helios.

543
00:37:49.561 --> 00:37:51.480
Well. I am not opposed to a summit

544
00:37:51.563 --> 00:37:53.982
but we would have
to include the other M-7 nations.

545
00:37:54.066 --> 00:37:55.400
Of course.

546
00:37:56.151 --> 00:38:00.447
and we will be more than happy
to host them here in Soviet Union.

547
00:38:01.281 --> 00:38:02.282
[chuckles]

548
00:38:03.534 --> 00:38:05.077
With all due respect. Irina.

549
00:38:05.744 --> 00:38:08.539
I think a neutral location would be
the most sensible

550
00:38:08.622 --> 00:38:10.749
in light of the nature of this conference.

551
00:38:12.209 --> 00:38:14.586
I need to give Korzhenko some sign
of your contrition

552
00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:16.755
if I am to lure him back to the table.

553
00:38:20.968 --> 00:38:22.302
Administrator Hobson?

554
00:38:23.762 --> 00:38:24.763
[sighs]

555
00:38:26.807 --> 00:38:27.808
All right.

556
00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:30.102
I will talk to the president.

557
00:38:35.148 --> 00:38:37.192
Javi. come set the table.

558
00:38:45.784 --> 00:38:47.077
[Javi groans]

559
00:38:48.328 --> 00:38:51.623
You know. you wouldn't even be alive
if we didn't do stuff like that.

560
00:38:51.707 --> 00:38:53.083
Please stop.

561
00:38:53.166 --> 00:38:55.002
[cell phone rings. buzzes]

562
00:39:00.090 --> 00:39:01.508
- [cell phone beeps]
- Hello.

563
00:39:02.176 --> 00:39:05.262
Hey. it's Brandt. The M-7 just announced
an emergency summit

564
00:39:05.345 --> 00:39:07.931
to hash out
how much everyone gets of this asteroid.

565
00:39:08.599 --> 00:39:09.600
Okay.

566
00:39:10.309 --> 00:39:11.476
Thank you for the update.

567
00:39:11.560 --> 00:39:14.313
It starts first thing next week. so...

568
00:39:14.396 --> 00:39:16.148
- But...
- ...you better start preparing.

569
00:39:17.482 --> 00:39:20.235
Dev will already be on his way
to Mars by then.

570
00:39:20.736 --> 00:39:22.863
Yep. Pack warm.

571
00:39:22.946 --> 00:39:24.448
You're going to the Soviet Union.

572
00:39:24.948 --> 00:39:25.949
[line clicks]

573
00:39:26.825 --> 00:39:27.826
[cell phone beeps]

574
00:39:52.142 --> 00:39:54.102
[whispering] Mommy loves you. Alex.

575
00:39:55.812 --> 00:39:56.980
Always.

576
00:40:39.314 --> 00:40:40.858
[Karen] God. I miss you.

577
00:40:42.693 --> 00:40:44.903
I miss you so much. [chuckles]

578
00:40:46.363 --> 00:40:48.073
I wish I could be there right now.

579
00:40:49.867 --> 00:40:52.953
I do. Not that... Not that you need me.

580
00:40:53.537 --> 00:40:59.793
Because you are so strong.
and you got this. Kelly. You've got this.

581
00:41:01.378 --> 00:41:03.589
You're stronger than me.

582
00:41:04.673 --> 00:41:07.217
Stronger than all of us put together.

583
00:41:07.968 --> 00:41:09.386
You got this. okay?

584
00:41:10.345 --> 00:41:14.016
And you are gonna be the best mom.
[chuckles]

585
00:41:14.099 --> 00:41:15.517
You are. I keep...

586
00:41:16.268 --> 00:41:20.606
I keep thinking
about how nurturing you've always been.

587
00:41:21.815 --> 00:41:26.236
From the day that your dad and I met you.
you've nurtured everybody around you.

588
00:41:27.404 --> 00:41:29.031
Even your dad and me. [chuckles]

589
00:41:29.114 --> 00:41:30.532
[sniffles]

590
00:41:30.616 --> 00:41:33.410
[sighs]
I can't wait to meet my little grandbaby.

591
00:41:35.245 --> 00:41:36.246
I may have...

592
00:41:36.330 --> 00:41:40.584
I may have already purchased the wallpaper
and the crib for the nursery. [chuckles]

593
00:41:40.667 --> 00:41:44.630
No. I know but I can't help it. [sighs]

594
00:41:47.174 --> 00:41:48.258
I love you...

595
00:41:50.135 --> 00:41:51.678
with all my heart.

596
00:41:56.266 --> 00:41:57.267
[line clicks]

597
00:42:00.270 --> 00:42:01.730
[sobbing]

598
00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:21.625
Show me the angular velocity estimates
for Asteroid 2003LC.

599
00:42:24.586 --> 00:42:26.296
[sighs] That's what I thought.

600
00:42:28.507 --> 00:42:29.967
[Ed muttering] ...goat rope.

601
00:42:48.652 --> 00:42:50.112
We need your speech. babe.

602
00:42:51.029 --> 00:42:54.324
Zay won't admit it but he really wants you
to be a big part of the ceremony.

603
00:42:55.033 --> 00:42:57.244
You know. my mom blessed my marriage
to his mother

604
00:42:57.327 --> 00:42:59.746
and now he wants you to bless his.

605
00:43:00.914 --> 00:43:02.666
I know you got a lot on your mind
up there.

606
00:43:02.749 --> 00:43:06.044
All we're seeing on the news is
how important this thing is

607
00:43:06.128 --> 00:43:08.088
and how much y'all gotta do.

608
00:43:08.797 --> 00:43:11.925
But. you know. it's okay
to step out of things for a minute.

609
00:43:12.009 --> 00:43:13.552
Sometimes it helps.

610
00:43:14.678 --> 00:43:16.597
I know whatever
you come up with will be great.

611
00:43:17.598 --> 00:43:18.932
Love you. [clicks tongue]

612
00:43:19.016 --> 00:43:20.017
[line clicks]

613
00:43:35.407 --> 00:43:36.491
[sighs]

614
00:43:40.037 --> 00:43:41.246
[sighs]

615
00:43:41.914 --> 00:43:43.498
Courtney. Isaiah.

616
00:43:44.499 --> 00:43:45.501
I...

617
00:43:46.627 --> 00:43:48.629
I wish I could be there
with you all today.

618
00:43:49.671 --> 00:43:51.715
I am so happy for you.

619
00:43:53.509 --> 00:43:57.262
Marriage. partnerships... It's. uh...

620
00:44:00.641 --> 00:44:01.642
It's...

621
00:44:18.408 --> 00:44:19.409
[line clicks]

622
00:44:58.073 --> 00:44:59.741
[no audible dialogue]

623
00:45:28.770 --> 00:45:31.607
[Danielle] After this.
there's nothing left.

624
00:45:32.733 --> 00:45:34.026
I have to tell him.

625
00:45:39.239 --> 00:45:40.365
I'll come with you.

626
00:45:44.494 --> 00:45:45.495
Okay.

627
00:46:12.523 --> 00:46:13.524
[Danielle] Danny?

628
00:46:21.573 --> 00:46:22.574
Danny?

629
00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:12.666
[knocks]

630
00:47:12.749 --> 00:47:13.750
[Dev] Come in.

631
00:47:17.671 --> 00:47:19.047
Do you have a minute. Dev?

632
00:47:20.382 --> 00:47:21.675
Sure.

633
00:47:30.309 --> 00:47:32.394
I've given it a lot of thought. and...

634
00:47:34.605 --> 00:47:36.398
I want to go to Mars with you.

635
00:47:37.482 --> 00:47:41.987
Our work is incredibly important to me
and it's important that it's done right.

636
00:47:44.364 --> 00:47:45.490
But here's the thing...

637
00:47:47.868 --> 00:47:49.745
I want to bring my son with me.

638
00:47:51.455 --> 00:47:56.877
I know it sounds crazy with his health
issues and all. but just hear me out.

639
00:47:59.421 --> 00:48:01.798
I spoke to some of my former colleagues
at NASA.

640
00:48:01.882 --> 00:48:04.468
plus the flight surgeons here at Helios.
and they all agreed

641
00:48:04.551 --> 00:48:08.138
that Alex's cardiopulmonary
issues might actually improve on Mars.

642
00:48:09.097 --> 00:48:11.892
His weaker heart won't have to pump
as hard in one-third gravity.

643
00:48:11.975 --> 00:48:15.604
and the higher oxygen concentrations
inside the base will help offset

644
00:48:15.687 --> 00:48:17.189
his lower lung capacity.

645
00:48:18.273 --> 00:48:20.651
Yes. the month of travel
will be challenging.

646
00:48:22.027 --> 00:48:24.655
but space travel's become safe.

647
00:48:25.989 --> 00:48:26.990
Routine.

648
00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:31.495
Besides. what seven-year-old wouldn't
wanna be weightless for a few weeks?

649
00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:36.959
I'd tutor him in my free time
so he'd still get an education.

650
00:48:37.042 --> 00:48:39.503
He won't interfere
with the functionality of the base.

651
00:48:39.586 --> 00:48:42.548
and my dad will help look after him
as well.

652
00:48:45.592 --> 00:48:50.097
Dev. I am committed to doing my job
to the best of my ability...

653
00:48:52.432 --> 00:48:54.518
but I can't just abandon my son.

654
00:48:59.439 --> 00:49:00.691
I hope you understand.

655
00:49:04.528 --> 00:49:05.529
[Dev] 'Course I do.

656
00:49:07.239 --> 00:49:08.323
and he'll be welcome.

657
00:49:13.453 --> 00:49:14.454
Thank you.

658
00:49:38.061 --> 00:49:39.938
[door opens]

659
00:49:40.022 --> 00:49:42.858
Milosh. how did we do today?

660
00:49:42.941 --> 00:49:46.069
Great. That new deodorant is flying
off the shelves.

661
00:49:46.153 --> 00:49:49.156
I think that loading dock supervisor
might be turning into a problem.

662
00:49:49.239 --> 00:49:51.283
- Hmm.
- Faiza thinks she's got a way around it

663
00:49:51.366 --> 00:49:54.995
but that. as they say.
is tomorrow's problem.

664
00:49:55.913 --> 00:49:56.997
Yes. You're right.

665
00:49:57.080 --> 00:49:59.374
Tomorrow's problem. [chuckles]

666
00:50:04.421 --> 00:50:05.422
Pleasure.

667
00:50:06.215 --> 00:50:07.674
Don't you want to count it?

668
00:50:09.134 --> 00:50:10.886
That's all right. I'm sure it's right.

669
00:50:12.679 --> 00:50:13.597
[chuckles]

670
00:50:15.015 --> 00:50:16.183
Let us drink.

671
00:50:17.309 --> 00:50:18.560
To the success.

672
00:50:21.063 --> 00:50:22.940
And to you. Milosh.

673
00:50:23.023 --> 00:50:24.066
No.

674
00:50:27.236 --> 00:50:28.570
To us.

675
00:50:28.654 --> 00:50:30.572
Na zazdrovye.

676
00:50:31.782 --> 00:50:33.408
[speaks Russian]

677
00:50:41.542 --> 00:50:43.418
[clears throat] Every time.

678
00:50:44.211 --> 00:50:45.337
[chuckles]

679
00:51:05.440 --> 00:51:06.441
What's this?

680
00:51:07.442 --> 00:51:08.402
[door closes]

681
00:51:12.531 --> 00:51:13.574
Ed. I'm...

682
00:51:14.408 --> 00:51:15.742
[sighs]

683
00:51:15.826 --> 00:51:18.412
I've thought long and hard about this.

684
00:51:19.913 --> 00:51:22.958
and I think it might be time for you
to take a step back from flight duty.

685
00:51:24.877 --> 00:51:26.086
Excuse me?

686
00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:29.298
Might be for the best.
You let somebody else command Ranger.

687
00:51:30.424 --> 00:51:31.884
[scoffs] Who. like you?

688
00:51:32.467 --> 00:51:34.803
No. It's not about that.

689
00:51:37.306 --> 00:51:39.308
I want you to let the doc
take a look at your hand.

690
00:51:39.391 --> 00:51:40.684
[scoffs]

691
00:51:40.767 --> 00:51:43.228
My hand. For what?

692
00:51:45.147 --> 00:51:46.440
You know what for.

693
00:51:53.113 --> 00:51:56.867
This is totally out of line. Danielle.

694
00:51:56.950 --> 00:51:59.411
I thought we were putting aside
our differences. but I guess

695
00:51:59.494 --> 00:52:01.246
that was just a load of bullshit.

696
00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:03.916
Ed. you have been commanding missions.

697
00:52:03.999 --> 00:52:08.295
flying missions. while concealing
a potentially serious health condition.

698
00:52:08.378 --> 00:52:10.714
All because what?
You just... You just couldn't let go.

699
00:52:10.797 --> 00:52:14.343
I know my body. I know what works for it.
I'm fine.

700
00:52:14.426 --> 00:52:17.221
That is not your call to make
and you know that.

701
00:52:18.639 --> 00:52:21.850
You lied to me.
How am I supposed to trust you?

702
00:52:21.934 --> 00:52:24.269
Come on. Danielle.
You know I'd never put anyone in danger.

703
00:52:24.353 --> 00:52:26.104
I'm not so sure I do anymore.

704
00:52:26.897 --> 00:52:30.901
You should've gone home a long time ago.
Be with your daughter and your grandson.

705
00:52:30.984 --> 00:52:31.985
Oh.

706
00:52:32.694 --> 00:52:33.695
Is...

707
00:52:34.571 --> 00:52:36.448
Is that why you went home so quickly?

708
00:52:36.990 --> 00:52:37.991
Hmm?

709
00:52:38.700 --> 00:52:39.952
Be with your family?

710
00:52:43.121 --> 00:52:45.999
Or maybe it was because
you're the one really running away.

711
00:52:47.376 --> 00:52:48.502
Watch yourself. Ed.

712
00:52:48.585 --> 00:52:49.586
Or what?

713
00:52:49.670 --> 00:52:51.755
You're already talking
about clipping my wings.

714
00:52:51.839 --> 00:52:52.965
What else is there?

715
00:52:53.048 --> 00:52:55.634
You gonna exile me
to that North Korean capsule?

716
00:52:56.468 --> 00:52:57.386
Huh?

717
00:52:58.262 --> 00:52:59.763
Give me a Bible to read?

718
00:53:00.806 --> 00:53:03.100
- Fuck you!
- There it is.

719
00:53:03.183 --> 00:53:04.393
Fuck you!

720
00:53:05.936 --> 00:53:09.439
I have been putting up with your shit
for the last 30 years!

721
00:53:09.940 --> 00:53:13.193
Watching you make wrong decision
after wrong decision.

722
00:53:13.277 --> 00:53:17.865
only thinking about yourself
like you're God's gift to the cosmos.

723
00:53:19.032 --> 00:53:21.702
Well. I have news for you. Ed Baldwin.

724
00:53:21.785 --> 00:53:25.873
You are just a pathetic old man
who doesn't know when to call it a day.

725
00:53:25.956 --> 00:53:28.917
Yeah. Well. unlike you.
I'm not a fucking quitter.

726
00:53:29.001 --> 00:53:33.338
No. Ed. And luckily. that is
not your concern anymore.

727
00:53:33.422 --> 00:53:34.423
You're done.

728
00:53:34.506 --> 00:53:37.342
[scoffs] What the hell you talking about?

729
00:53:38.093 --> 00:53:41.138
You are hereby removed from flight status

730
00:53:41.722 --> 00:53:44.683
and relieved of your duties
as XO on this base.

731
00:53:45.684 --> 00:53:46.977
Come on. Danielle.

732
00:53:49.563 --> 00:53:51.648
Don't do anything you're gonna regret.

